com.abmash.api
Class Browser

java.lang.Object
  com.abmash.api.Browser
All Implemented Interfaces:
com.abmash.core.Document
public class Browser
extends java.lang.Object
implements com.abmash.core.Document

Main class for using a browser instance and interacting with it. You are encouraged to use more than one browser instance to interact with more than one page at a time. This can prove useful if you are switching between the same pages multiple times.

Examples:

  • browser.click("Save"); clicks on a link or button labeled Save
  • browser.type("Username", "Jack"); enter the text Jack in the input field labeled Username
  • browser.select("language", "english"); selects the options english in the dropdown/list labeled language
  • HtmlElement firstTitle = browser.query().isTitle().findFirst(); finds the first title element on the current page and saves them
  • HtmlElements imagesLeftToTitle = browser.query().isImage().leftTo(title).find(); finds all image elements left to the previously found title

Elements can be searched by queries to get their values and text, and to interact with them. Search queries are case-sensitive.

Use click(String) to search for elements with the specified name or label and click the best match.

Use type(String, String) to search for input elements (usually <input> or <textarea>, but also rich text editors used by many CMS, forums or blog applications) with the specified name or label, get the best match and enter the given text.

Use choose(String, String) to search for <select> elements (usually a dropdown selection or a box with a list of options) with the specified name or label, get the best match and select the given option from the list.

Use query() to create an HtmlQuery instance and to search for HtmlElement instances. Search conditions can be chained one after another. The call of HtmlQuery.find() or HtmlQuery.findFirst() will return the result(s). Found elements can be further interacted with, see HtmlElement.

Author:
Alper Ortac
See Also:
HtmlQuery, HtmlElement

Constructor Detail

Browser

public Browser(java.lang.String url)
Starts new browser session. Opens the browser, loads the given URL and waits until it is ready.

The default browser configuration is the use of Firefox 4 and can be overwritten by creating a default.properties file. TODO explanation properties. For further customization see also Browser(String, BrowserConfig).

Each browser instance needs to be closed at the end of the program by calling the close() method. Use openUrl(String) to open another URL in the browser.

Parameters:
url - The URL to open, set to null to prevent loading a page
See Also:
close(), openUrl(String)

query

public HtmlQuery query()
Creates HtmlQuery instance to find element on current page.

Examples:

  • browser.query().has("result").findFirst(); searches for elements containing the attribute or inner text result
  • browser.query().isClickable().findFirst(); searches for clickable elements like links and buttons
  • for more examples see HtmlQuery

Description:

Define conditions by chaining is, has, tag and select methods. Get the query result by executing HtmlQuery.find() or HtmlQuery.findFirst().

Returns:
HtmlQuery instance to add an arbitrary number of find conditions
See Also:
HtmlQuery

click

public HtmlElement click(java.lang.String query)
Searches for a clickable element with specified query string and clicks it.

Example:

  • browser.click("Save"); clicks on a link or button labeled Save

Description:

Elements having an attribute value or visible text containing the query string will be added to the result set. The first result will be used for clicking. If you already have an HtmlElement instance use HtmlElement.click() instead.

Note that if the page reloads after a click, all found HtmlElement instances may lose their validity.

Parameters:
query - element attribute value or inner text containing this string
Returns:
HtmlElement to further interact with that element or null if element could not be found
See Also:
HtmlElement.click()

type

public HtmlElement type(java.lang.String query,
                        java.lang.String text)
Searches for element with specified query string and enters the text.

Example:

  • browser.type("location","New York").submit(); types in the text New York in the input field named or labeled location and then submits the form which contains that element.

Description:

Elements having an attribute value or visible text containing the query string will be added to the result set. The first result will be used for typing in the text. If you already have an HtmlElement instance use HtmlElement.type(String) instead. Use HtmlElement.submit() on the returned object to submit the form.

Parameters:
query - element attribute value or inner text containing this string
text - the text to type in
Returns:
HtmlElement to further interact with the form element, for instance to HtmlElement.submit() the form, or null if element could not be found
See Also:
HtmlElement.type(String)

getList

public List getList(java.lang.String query)

Example:

  • List ingredientTable = browser.getTable("Ingredient"); returns the first table which contains the text Ingredient.
  • ingredientTable.get(0); returns the first list item.

Parameters:
query - text which is contained in the list (visible text or attribute value)
Returns:
List representation of this element
See Also:
List

getList

public List getList(HtmlElement listElement)
Returns the List representation of a <ul>, <ol> or <dl> element.

Example:

  • HtmlElement listTitle = browser.query().isTitle().has("Ingredients").findFirst(); Returns the first element being a title labeled Ingredients
  • HtmlElement list = browser.query().isList().below(tableTitle).findFirst(); returns the first list below the previously selected title element
  • List ingredientList = browser.getList(table); finally returns the list representation.
  • ingredientList.get(0); returns the first list item.
  • See List for more examples on how to interact with the table.

Parameters:
listElement - has to be an HtmlElement with the tag <ul>, <ol> or <dl>
Returns:
List representation of this element
See Also:
List

getTable

public Table getTable(java.lang.String query)
Finds the first table whose visible text or attribute values contains the given search query, and the Table representation.

Example:

  • Table userTable = browser.getTable("User"); returns the first table which contains the text User.
  • userTable.get(0, "email"); returns the email address of the user in the first row.

Parameters:
query - text which is contained in the table (visible text or attribute value)
Returns:
Table representation of this element
See Also:
Table

getTable

public Table getTable(HtmlElement tableElement)
Returns the Table representation of a <table> element.

Example:

  • HtmlElement tableTitle = browser.query().isTitle().has("Userlist").findFirst(); Returns the first element being a title labeled Userlist
  • HtmlElement table = browser.query().isTable().below(tableTitle).findFirst(); returns the first table below the previously selected title element
  • Table userTable = browser.getTable(table); finally returns the table representation.
  • userTable.getCell(0, "email"); returns the email address of the user in the first row.
  • See Table for more examples on how to interact with the table.

Parameters:
tableElement - has to be an HtmlElement with the tag <table>
Returns:
Table representation of this element
See Also:
Table
